  <title>Exercises</title>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
    <p>Let <m>G</m> be a group and let <m>H\leq G</m> have index 2. Prove that <m>H\unlhd G</m>.</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>

    <p>
     Let <m>a\in G</m>. If <m>a\in H</m>, then <m>aH=H=Ha</m>. On the other hand, if <m>a\not\in H</m>, then <m>aH=G-H=Ha</m>, since <m>(G:H)=2</m>. Thus, <m>H\unlhd G</m>.

    </p>
  </solution>
  </exercise>

<exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>Let <m>G</m> be an abelian group with <m>N\unlhd G</m>. Prove that <m>G/N</m> is abelian.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
 
    <p>Let <m>aN,bN\in G/N.</m> Then <me>(aN)(bN)=abN=baN=(bN)(aN).</me> So <m>G/N</m> is abelian.
     
    </p>
  </solution>
  </exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Find the following.
<ol>
<li><m>|2\Z/6\Z|</m></li>
<li><m>|H|</m>, for <m>H=2+\langle 6\rangle \subseteq \Z_{12}</m></li>
<li><m>o(2+\langle 6\rangle)</m> in <m>\Z_{12}/\langle 6\rangle</m></li>
<li><m>\langle fH\rangle </m> in <m>D_4/H</m>, where <m>H=\{e,r^2\}</m></li>
<li><m>|(\Z_6\times \Z_8)/(\langle 3\rangle\times \langle 2\rangle)|</m></li>


<li><m>|(\Z_{15} \times \Z_{24})/\langle (5,4)\rangle|</m></li>

</ol>

</p>


</statement>
<solution>

<p>
<ol>
<li><m>|2\Z/6\Z|=(2\Z:6\Z)=3</m></li>
<li><m>\langle 6\rangle=\{6,0\}</m>, so <m>|H|=|\{8,2\}|=2</m></li>
<li><m>o(2+\langle 6\rangle)=3</m></li>
<li><m>\langle fH\rangle= \{fH, H\}</m></li>
<li><m>|\Z_6\times \Z_8|=6(8)=48</m> and <m>|\langle 3\rangle \times \langle 2\rangle|=2(4)=8</m>, so <m>|(\Z_6\times \Z_8)/(\langle 3\rangle\times \langle 2\rangle)|=48/8=6</m>.</li>
<li><m>\langle (5,4)\rangle=\{(5,4),(10,8),(0,12),(5,16),(10,20),(0,0)\}</m>; so the order
of <m>(\Z_{15} \times \Z_{24})/\langle (5,4)\rangle</m> is <m>\frac{(15)(24)}{6}=60</m>.</li>
</ol>
</p>
</solution>

</exercise>


<exercise>
<statement><p>  For each of the following, find a familiar group to which the given group is isomorphic. (Hint: Consider the group order, properties such as abelianness and cyclicity, group tables, orders of elements, etc.)


<ol>
<li><m>\Z/14\Z</m></li>
<li><m>3\Z/12\Z</m></li>
<li><m>S_8/A_8</m></li>
<li><m>(\Z_4 \times \Z_{15})/(\langle 2 \rangle \times \langle 3 \rangle )</m></li>
<li><m>D_4/\langle r^2 \rangle</m></li>

</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
<ol>
<li><m>\Z_{14}</m></li>
<li><m>3\Z/12\Z</m> is cyclic (since <m>3\Z</m> is cyclic) with order 4, so is isomorphic to <m>\Z_4</m>. </li>
<li><m>S_8/A_8</m> has order 2, so is isomorphic to <m>\Z_2</m>.</li>

<li>Since <m>\gcd(4,15)=1</m>, the group <m>4\Z \times 15\Z</m> is cyclic. So since <m>|4\Z \times 15\Z|/|\langle 2 \rangle \times \langle 3 \rangle|=60/10=6</m>, we have  <m>(4\Z \times 15\Z)/(\langle 2 \rangle \times \langle 3 \rangle) \simeq \Z_6</m>.
</li>
<li><m>|D_4/\langle r^2\rangle|=8/2=4</m>, and <m>f\langle r^2\rangle</m> and <m>r\langle r^2\rangle</m> in <m>D_4/\langle r^2\rangle</m> each have order 2, so
<m>D_4/\langle r^2 \rangle \simeq \Z_2^2</m>.</li>
</ol>
</p>
</solution>

</exercise>



<exercise>
<statement><p>  Let <m>H\unlhd G</m> with index <m>k</m>, and let <m>a\in G</m>. Prove that <m>a^k\in H</m>.</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
Since <m>k=(G:H)</m>, <m>|G/H|=k</m>.  Then 
<m>aH\in G/H</m> has an order, call it <m>d</m>, which must divide <m>|G/H|=k</m>.
So <m>k=dm</m> for some <m>m\in \Z</m>.  Then
<m>(aH)^k=(aH)^{dm}=((aH)^d)^m=H^m=H</m>. Since <m>(aH)^k=a^kH</m>, we thus
have <m>a^kH=H</m>, implying that <m>a^k\in H</m>, as desired.
</p>
</solution>
</exercise>
